Diet Recommendations I recommend an antiinflammatory diet for patients with mental illness. At its core, this means eating real foods that are non processed. The 3 golden rules are: Eat Real Food Mostly Plants Not Too Much Real foods means foods you can easily identify as coming from a farm, plant, or animal. These include vegatables, fruits, legumes, nuts, oils, dairy, eggs, and clean meats (grass fed or wild caught). Avoid foods that are processed, include unrecognizable chemicals or ingredients, grains, gluten, and sugar of all kinds. Do not eat charred meats or meats with nitrites. Eat meals that are 50% fruits, veggies, nuts, and legumes. Protein portions should be the size of your closed fist. Try to eat some green leafy vegetables every day (Kale, lettuce, spinach, chard). Avoid high carb and glutenous foods such as bread and pasta. Meal portions should be moderate, roughly 700 calories total for a total of 2000 calories per day. Fasting for 16 hours out of the day (eating only breakfast and lunch or dinner and lunch) can decrease inflammation in some cases but is not recommended for those with low blood sugar. Avoid caffiene after noon and avoid alcohol in general. Lifestyle Recommendations We recommend the following lifestyle modifications for you: Get at least 8 hours of sleep in a cool, dark room. Adults sleep optimally at low temperatures (around 66 degrees). Do not take stimulants or drink coffee after noon. Do you not use your bed for anything other than sleep and sex. Avoid screens and bright lights 1 hour before bed. If you cannot sleep for more than 20 minutes get out of bed and either sleep somewhere else (couch) or do a light, non stimulating activity until you are fully tired. Meditation and mindfullness practices are highly recommended, and are often easier than you think. I recommend using a smart phone app such as Calm or Insight Timer. You can either use one of the guided meditations or just set a time and meditate on your own. How to meditate: 1. Set a time for 10 minutes. 2. Close your eyes and focus on the inhalation and exhalation of your breath. 3. Try to focus on a specific part of your body connected to your breath such as your nostrils or belly. Focus on the air going through your nostrils or your belly rising and falling. 4. When you get distracted (everyone does), not the distraction and bring your attention back to the breath. 5. Keep bringing your attention back to the breath until the timer goes off. Don't be discouraged if you are frequently distracted, thats the point! Reorienting your attention is what meditation is. If you have trouble focusing on your breath, try counting each inhalation and exhalation up to ten, then start over. Exercise is better for mental health than most medications. I recommend at least 150 minutes of cardiovascular exercise per week. This includes things like running, walking, playing group or invidual sports, bicycling, or using an elliptical. The best type of exercise is the type you enjoy, because that makes it easy to do consistently. Start from where you are at: If you can only run for one minute, start there and do 2 minutes the next time. Social activity has been found to decrease the risk of mental and physical illness. Try to spend several hours per week in social situations, including being with friends and family, talking to coworkers, group activites, group sports, civic meetings, or shared interest groups. Spending time in nature has been shown to have antidepressant and anti anxiety properties. I recommend at least 30 minutes in nature per week.

The diagnosis of psychiatric illness is a complex integration of history, psychiatric, medical and physical findings, social and developmental history, history of substance abuse as well as MSE. Considerations include mood disorders, psychotic disorders, substance induced disorders, anxiety and trauma disorders, and many others. These have all been considered in formulating the diagnoses/diagnosis below. This may change as more information arises and further diagnostic clarification is performed. Major depressive disorder, single episode, moderate [F32.1] . Diet Recommendations I recommend an antiinflammatory diet for patients with mental illness. At its core, this means eating real foods that are non processed. The 3 golden rules are: Eat Real Food Mostly Plants Not Too Much Real foods means foods you can easily identify as coming from a farm, plant, or animal. These include vegatables, fruits, legumes, nuts, oils, dairy, eggs, and clean meats (grass fed or wild caught). Avoid foods that are processed, include unrecognizable chemicals or ingredients, grains, gluten, and sugar of all kinds. Do not eat charred meats or meats with nitrites. Eat meals that are 50% fruits, veggies, nuts, and legumes. Protein portions should be the size of your closed fist. Try to eat some green leafy vegetables every day (Kale, lettuce, spinach, chard). Avoid high carb and glutenous foods such as bread and pasta. Meal portions should be moderate, roughly 700 calories total for a total of 2000 calories per day. Fasting for 16 hours out of the day (eating only breakfast and lunch or dinner and lunch) can decrease inflammation in some cases but is not recommended for those with low blood sugar. Avoid caffiene after noon and avoid alcohol in general. Lifestyle Recommendations We recommend the following lifestyle modifications for you: Get at least 8 hours of sleep in a cool, dark room. Adults sleep optimally at low temperatures (around 66 degrees). Do not take stimulants or drink coffee after noon. Do you not use your bed for anything other than sleep and sex. Avoid screens and bright lights 1 hour before bed. If you cannot sleep for more than 20 minutes get out of bed and either sleep somewhere else (couch) or do a light, non stimulating activity until you are fully tired. Meditation and mindfullness practices are highly recommended, and are often easier than you think. I recommend using a smart phone app such as Calm or Insight Timer. You can either use one of the guided meditations or just set a time and meditate on your own. How to meditate: 1. Set a time for 10 minutes. 2. Close your eyes and focus on the inhalation and exhalation of your breath. 3. Try to focus on a specific part of your body connected to your breath such as your nostrils or belly. Focus on the air going through your nostrils or your belly rising and falling. 4. When you get distracted (everyone does), not the distraction and bring your attention back to the breath. 5. Keep bringing your attention back to the breath until the timer goes off. Don't be discouraged if you are frequently distracted, thats the point! Reorienting your attention is what meditation is. If you have trouble focusing on your breath, try counting each inhalation and exhalation up to ten, then start over. Exercise is better for mental health than most medications. I recommend at least 150 minutes of cardiovascular exercise per week. This includes things like running, walking, playing group or invidual sports, bicycling, or using an elliptical. The best type of exercise is the type you enjoy, because that makes it easy to do consistently. Start from where you are at: If you can only run for one minute, start there and do 2 minutes the next time. Social activity has been found to decrease the risk of mental and physical illness. Try to spend several hours per week in social situations, including being with friends and family, talking to coworkers, group activites, group sports, civic meetings, or shared interest groups.
